vectorData.altText: That's right!  A spinal nerve (H) is a mixed nerve which contains both sensory and motor fibres.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Sensory information from somatic and visceral sources in the periphery enters the spinal cord via the dorsal roots. The cell bodies of these sensory neurons are located in the dorsal root ganglia (DRG). Many of these sensory neurons synapse onto neurons in the dorsal horn of the spinal cord.
Motor information destined for both somatic and visceral targets leaves the spinal cord via the ventral roots. The cell bodies of somatic motor neurons are located in the ventral horn of the spinal cord. The cell bodies of any visceral motor neurons are located in an intermediate position between the dorsal and ventral horns. If they are sympathetic, they form the lateral horns of T1-L2. If they are parasympathetic, they are restricted to levels S2-S4
Lesions of ventral horn cells, spinal nerves or their roots causes sensory and / or motor signs in a dermatomal / myotomal distribution.

Peripheral nerves contain both sensory fibres carrying information toward the CNS and motor fibres carrying information away from the CNS, to peripheral targets. These modalities, which are mixed at the level of the spinal nerve, are segregated at the level of the spinal nerve roots.
